## Yes! Virtual Threads DO Run on CPU!

This is a very common misconception. Let me clear it up.

---

## How Virtual Threads Actually Work

Virtual threads are **not** magic — they still need CPU to execute. They run **mounted** on a real OS thread called a **Carrier Thread**.

```
JVM
 │
 ├── Carrier Thread 1 (OS/Platform Thread) ──► CPU Core 1
 │        │
 │    Virtual Thread A (running)
 │
 ├── Carrier Thread 2 (OS/Platform Thread) ──► CPU Core 2
 │        │
 │    Virtual Thread B (running)
```

---

## The Magic — What Happens on Blocking

```
Virtual Thread A running on Carrier Thread 1
        │
        │ hits Thread.sleep() or I/O
        │
        ▼
JVM UNMOUNTS Virtual Thread A   ◄── Key difference!
        │
Carrier Thread 1 is FREE
        │
        ▼
JVM MOUNTS Virtual Thread B onto Carrier Thread 1
        │
Virtual Thread B now runs on CPU
```

With **platform threads**, the OS thread just sits idle and wastes CPU time during blocking.

---

## Side by Side

```java
// Platform Thread
Thread.ofPlatform().start(() -> {
    callAPI(); // OS thread STUCK waiting — CPU idle, thread wasted
});

// Virtual Thread
Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {
    callAPI(); // Virtual thread unmounted — carrier thread FREE for other work
});
```

---

## CPU Bound Work — Virtual vs Platform

```java
// CPU heavy task
Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {
    // Virtual thread stays MOUNTED the whole time
    // Never unmounts because there's no blocking
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++) {
        Math.sqrt(i); // pure CPU
    }
});
```

For CPU work, virtual threads **never unmount** — they behave exactly like platform threads.
That's why ForkJoinPool is still better for CPU-heavy work.

---

## Simple Mental Model

```
Virtual Thread = Carrier Thread (CPU) + Smart Parking

Blocking happens?
    → Park the virtual thread (save its state)
    → Free the carrier thread for others
    → Resume when blocking is done

No blocking?
    → Stays on carrier thread
    → Runs normally on CPU
```

---

## Bottom Line

| | Virtual Thread | Platform Thread |
|---|---|---|
| Runs on CPU | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Blocked on I/O | Unmounts, frees carrier | Stuck, wastes OS thread |
| CPU bound work | Stays mounted | Stays mounted |
| Carrier threads | = CPU cores (small) | = OS threads (limited) |

> Virtual threads **do run on CPU** via carrier threads.
> The advantage is purely in **blocking scenarios** — they yield the carrier thread instead of wasting it.
> For pure CPU work, they offer **no advantage** over platform threads.

## Great Question! One Carrier CAN Host Many Virtual Threads!

---

## The Key Insight — Time Sharing

A carrier thread doesn't have one dedicated virtual thread. It picks up **whatever virtual thread is ready to run.**

```
Time ──────────────────────────────────────────►

Carrier Thread 1:
  [VT-A running] [VT-B running] [VT-D running] [VT-A resumed] [VT-C running]
        │               │              │
     VT-A blocks    VT-B blocks    VT-D blocks
     (unmounted)    (unmounted)    (unmounted)
```

---

## Concrete Example

```
Say you have 1 Carrier Thread and 4 Virtual Threads
Each virtual thread calls an API that takes 1 second

Platform Thread (1 OS thread, 4 tasks):
─────────────────────────────────────────────
[VT-A: 1s wait] [VT-B: 1s wait] [VT-C: 1s wait] [VT-D: 1s wait]
Total time = 4 seconds ❌ (sequential, thread blocked each time)


Virtual Thread (1 Carrier Thread, 4 virtual threads):
─────────────────────────────────────────────
t=0 : VT-A starts API call → blocks → unmounts
      VT-B starts API call → blocks → unmounts
      VT-C starts API call → blocks → unmounts
      VT-D starts API call → blocks → unmounts
t=1 : All 4 API calls return → all 4 resume
Total time = ~1 second ✅ (concurrent!)
```

---

## What Actually Happens Inside JVM

```
1 Carrier Thread managing 4 Virtual Threads:

t=0ms  → Mount VT-A, VT-A makes HTTP call
         VT-A BLOCKS → Unmount VT-A (parked)
         
t=1ms  → Mount VT-B, VT-B makes DB call  
         VT-B BLOCKS → Unmount VT-B (parked)

t=2ms  → Mount VT-C, VT-C makes file I/O
         VT-C BLOCKS → Unmount VT-C (parked)

t=1000ms → HTTP response arrives for VT-A
           Mount VT-A back → continues execution
           
t=1001ms → DB response arrives for VT-B
           Mount VT-B back → continues execution
```

---

## The Real Power — Scale This Up

```java
// 1 Million virtual threads — only ~8 carrier threads (CPU cores)
ExecutorService vExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

IntStream.range(0, 1_000_000).forEach(i ->
    vExec.submit(() -> {
        callExternalAPI(); // each blocks, unmounts, carrier is free
        return i;
    })
);

// Carrier threads are NEVER idle
// They constantly pick up ready virtual threads
// Like a waiter serving many tables, not standing at one table waiting
```

---

## Waiter Analogy 🧑‍🍳

```
Platform Thread = 1 waiter per table
  Waiter stands at table waiting for food to arrive
  Can't serve other tables meanwhile
  Need 1000 waiters for 1000 tables ❌

Virtual Thread = 1 waiter, many tables
  Takes order (starts task)
  Goes to other tables while kitchen prepares (blocking)
  Comes back when food is ready (unblocks)
  1 waiter handles 1000 tables ✅
```

---

## Bottom Line

> One carrier thread hosts **many** virtual threads — not just one.
> When a virtual thread blocks, carrier immediately picks up the **next ready virtual thread.**
> This is why 8 carrier threads can manage **millions** of virtual threads efficiently.
> The carrier is **never sitting idle** — it's always executing some ready virtual thread.
